children.text: The wall adjoining the sink, basin, or trough has not been made water resistant to a height of 150mm in accordance with the Building Code of Australia (BCA) and relevant Australian Standard AS 3740 to prevent water leaks into the structure that could cause damage.
Part 3.8.1.2 of the Building Code of Australia (NCC/BCA) - Wet Areas, states that;
‘Building elements in wet areas within a building must-
a) be waterproof or water resistant in accordance with Table 3.8.1.1; and

Table 3.8.1.1 in the NCC/BCA shows that the wall adjoining the vessel must be water resistant to 150mm high, and any penetrations that occur in the water resistant surfaces are required to be waterproof;

The builder must install a water resistant splashback, such as tiling (or similar) to at least 150mm high to the areas adjoining the sink, basin, or trough and fully waterproof around any penetrations within the 150mm high area, as required by the NCC’s Building Code of Australia and Australian Standard AS 3740.
